{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_1kahlo_ver01/data/sn83045462/0028060205A/1937111401/0707.xml":{"full_text":"FILIPINO ANNIVERSARY\nFINDS OLD ISSUE ALIVE\nEarly Independence Question, Long\nRegarded as Settled, Revived\nBy President Quezon.\nCBy JAMES G. WINGO.\nHE second anniversary tomor\nrow of the Philippine Com\nmonwealth will find the islands\nonce more engaged in an issue\nover early independence.\nPresident Manuel Quezon revived\nwhat had been considered ^a settled\nquestion when he proposed 'to Presi\ndent Roosevelt to ask Congress to\ngrant Philippine independence on De\ncember 30 (Filipino Hero-Martyr Jose\nRizal day), 1938, or July 4, 1939. Re\ncently Quezon announced that he\nwould not seek to amend the Philip\npine constitution to allow him to run\nfor a second six-year term. This leads\nobservers to believe that the long-time\nFilipino leader is ambitious to be\ncome the first president of the Phil\nippine Republic.\nUnder. the Philippine independence\nact, as written, the islands will be set\nfully free on July 4, 1946. Unless in\ndependence falls before November 15,\n1941, Quezon's successor will become\nthe new republic\u2019s first president.\nQuezon gave reasons not so per\nsonal as this, however. He recently\ntold his National Assembly that if\nthere were objections to independence\nnow, they will still exist in 1946.\nNew Deal Another Reason.\nAnother reason he gave for wanting\nearly independence is the New Deal.\n\"It will be to our best interests to se\ncure independence during and under\nthe administration of President Roose\nveil,, ne expiainea. i nave no aouDt\nthat under his leadership we will re\nceive from the Government of the\nUnited States the fairest treatment\nthat we may ever expect to receive\nunder the leadership of his suc\ncessors.\u201d\nOpposition to early independence,\nhowever, has grown tremendously in\nthe past two years. Sugar and coco\nnut planters and others whose busi\nnesses depend upon United States\nPhilippine reciprocal free trade have\nsucceeded in creating a public opinion\nfavorable to a continuation of the\nCommonwealth. A nation-wide poll\nrecently conducted by the American\nedited Philippines Free Press indicated\nthat 55.46 per cent of the people are\nagainst Quezon's early independence\nproposal.\nA joint preparatory committee on\nPhilippine affairs, composed of\nAmerican and Filipino experts ap\npointed by President Roosevelt and\nPresident Quezon, last week ended a\nthree-month study of economic con\nditions in the Philippines. The Amer\nican experts are now on their way\nback to Washington, but the Filipino\nmembers chose to remain in Manila\nbecause of a reported disagreement.\nIt had been previously reported that\nPresident Quezon once threatened to\nwithdraw the Filipino group. Am\nbassador John Van A. MacMurray,\nchairman of the committee, denied\nthat a split existed but admitted that\nmembers were not in agreement in all\nthings.\nChief Matters Discussed.\nMain problems given consideration\nby the committee were the character\nof the trade preferences which should\nexist for a specified limited period be\ntween the United States and the\nPhilippines; the precise arrangements\nfor governing the trade relations be\ntween the two countries after term\nination of preferential trade rela\ntions; economic adjustments that\ncould be undertaken in the Philippines\nand methods of executing and financ\ning them; the need or appropriateness\nof changes in the Philippine currency\nand banking system, and in the pro\nvisions for servicing Philippine bonded\nindebtedness, that may be required to\nimplement the plan for economic ad\njustment recommended by the joint\ncommittee; adequate protection of the\nrights and interests of the United\nStates and its citizens in the Philip\npines and of the Philippines and its\ncitizens in the United States after the\nattainment of independence, and the\nbearing which the possible negotiation\nof the neutralization agreement pro\nvided for in the Philippine independ\nence act would have on the problems\natudied by the committee.\nThe committee gave no consider\nation to the political relations be\ntween the two countries but took\ncognizance of the bearing which the\nadvancing of the date of Philippine\nindependence would have on the\nchances of the Philippine economic\nstructure to survive. The commit\ntee's report will be presented to Presi\ndent Roosevelt in December or early\nin January. High Commissioner Mc\nNutt will fly to Washington to discuss\nthe report with the President before\nhe makes recommendation to Con\ngress.\nDespite the uncertainty created by\nthe revival of the independent issue,\ngeneral prosperity exists in the Philip\npines. Although government ex\npenditures have grown considerably,\nno new taxes have been imposed. On\nthe other hand, one of the main\nsources of government revenue, the\npoll tax, was abolished recently.\nTax Refunds Important.\nThis prosperity has been brought\nabout by increased values of exports\nw Milieu WMOICO, liiUICOOCU Ollip\nmerits of gold bullion to this country,\nthe value of which now averages more\nthan $2,000,000 a month, and the tre\nmendous contributions made by the\nUnited States Treasury to the Philip\npine government in the form of re\nfunds of Philippine coconut oil tax\nand Philippine sugar processing tax.\nThese windfalls amount to more than\n$30,000,000 annually. Last summer\naccumulated collections of coconut oil\nexcise tax totaling approximately $50,\n000,000 were paid to the Philippine\ngovernment.\nAfter spending eight months abroad,\nPresident Quezon returned to Manila\nlast August and called the National\nAssembly, a unicameral body which\nhe Is now seeking to make bicameral,\nto a special session. He recommended\nmeans of spending the windfall from\nthe United States.\nPirst problem he tackled was the\nancient agrarian trouble, which ha$\ncaused sporadic uprisings In various\nparts of the archipelago. He recom\nmended the appropriation of $3,500,\n000 for the purchase of large haci\nendas. Observers were surprised by\nthe small size of the allotment. Que\nzon explained that if he announced\nthat the government would buy all\nlarge estates, those who would want\nto sell their haciendas would promptly\nstart tenant trouble. He said, how\never, that he was determined to\ndestroy the political power of haci\nenda owners, who control the social\nand political life in their respective\nbailiwicks.\nIn line with the Commonwealth\npolicy to develop Mindanao, Quezon\nrevealed that he had been In negotla\n\ni\ntion with the Goodyear Tire Rub\nber Co. for assistance in the develop\nment of rubber plantations in the\nsecond largest island of the archi\npelago. This company's 2,500-acre\nrubber plantation in Mindanao is\ncurrently earning a high yield, on\npar with the best in Sumatra. When\nQuezon was reminded that Firestone\nrefused to invest in the Philippines\nbecause of the limitation of corpor\nate landholding to 2,500 acres, he\nsaid both the sugar and coconut\nindustries has prospered under the\nsame limitation.\nOne of Quezon's current pet projects\nis the raising of wages in all industries\nnot only as a social justice reform, but\nalso as a means of spreading out to\nall the people the benefits of United\nStates-Philippine relationship, especi\nally free trade. Keen observers\npointed out that this plan does hot\njibe with his early independence pro\nposal. Inasmuch as those advocating\nindependence are mostly non-sharers\nof free trade benefits, it looks as if\nQuezon is fermenting public opinion\nagainst his early independence pro\nposal by making everybody have s\nproportionate share .of the fruits of\nUnited States-Philippine relationship\nAnother obvious reason for Quezon\u2019s\nsolicitude for the underpaid workers\nis that the newly-organized Philip\npine Popular Front is making con\nvoi__ J __ _4U-. _~__\nk'tuv*uv>v iivuu UUiUlig VltV\nThe Popular Front is a federation ol\nall the political organizations which\nsee virtual dictatorship in the Quezor\nadministration, including Bishop\nGregorio Aglipay's Republican party\nGen. Emilio Aguinaldo\u2019s National\nSocialist party, and Benigno Ramos'\nSakdalistas, the group which staged\na bloody uprising in 1935.\nMac Arthur Wins Approval.\nAlthough objections to universal\nmilitary service continue, the plan de\nsigned by Maj. Gen. Douglas Mac\nArthur is being carried out. The arm)\nhas the rebellious Moros under con\ntrol. However, the army has sup\nplanted education as the largest iteir\nof government expenditures. In the\nnext fiscal year national defense will\nco6t $12,500,000, about one-third ol\nthe total income of the Philippine\ngovernment (excluding the windfall!\nfrom the United States). Immense!)\nsatisfied with Gen. MacArthur, the\nfield marshal of the Philippine army\nthe National Assembly is seeking the\ncontinuance of his services upon hi!\nretirement from the United States\nArmy at the end of the year.\nWomen of the Philippines became\nlast May the first of their sex to be\ngranted suffrage in the Orient. Tak\ning advantage of their newly acquiree\nright, women are running for provin\ncial governors and municipal mayors\nin the long-delayed election next\nmonth.\nPointing out that radical groupe\nmay disturb the peace of the country\nPresident Quezon and the National\nAssembly postponed the election, con\nstitutionally set for last June. Itie\ncontinuation in office of every elective\nmunicipal and provincial official de\npended upon Quezon. Persistent cries\nof dictatorship finally led to the set\nting of the election next month. It\nis believed that, although a number ol\nPopular Front candidates will be cata\npulted into office on the dictatorship\nissue, the Fusion party, a coalition oi\nthe parties of Quezon and Vice Presi\ndent Sergio Osmena, will win hand\nsomely.\nJapanese Expansion Feared.\nPresident Quezon dismisses the Jap\nanese penetration of Mindanao witn\nthe remark. \u201cThere is no Japanese\nproblem in Davao,\u201d but Filipinos ere\nstill apprehensive of Japanese in\ncursions. \u201cRight now,\u201d they say, \u201cthe\nJapanese have their hands full in\nChina, but what will happen to our\ncountry when they are through there\nand resume their southward empire\nmarch?\u201d At the Manila hearings of\nthe joint preparatory committee of ex\nperts, Japanese frankly and unabash\nedly asked for equal economic and\ntrade privileges in the Philippines\nwith the United States.\nRelations between the High Com\nmissioner, the representative of the\nPresident of the United States in the\nPhilippines, and the Commonwealth,\nwhich was widely discussed editorially\nin the United States a few months ago,\nmay be described best by the following\nexcerpts from Quezon\u2019s recent message\nto the National Assembly:\n\u201cThe present United Slates High\nCommissioner has been but a few\nmonths in our midst. Some of his\nearly acts wrere misrepresented or mis\nunderstood. It is my pleasure\nand my duty to report to you\u2014and\nwhat I am going to say is no mere\ngesture of official courtesy, but an\nhonest and straight talk\u2014that I could\nwish for no better United States High\nCommissioner in the Philippines than\nhis excellency, Paul V. McNutt.\nSince my return we have had some\ndifficult problems to settle and I had\noccasion to appraise the measure of\nhim. He deserves our respect and\naffection. The best spirit of mutual\nco-operation characterizes our official\nassociation, and we have also become\ngood friends.\u201d\nOutstanding achievement of Com\nmissioner McNutt, besides his winning\nthe confidence of the Filipinos even\nafter he had made it plain that he, as\nrepresentative of the sovereign Gov\nwuucuv yicvcuco me U1 Hie\nPhilippines, is the repeal of the law\nwhich stopped the payments of pen\nsions to American teachers who had\nserved in the islands. McNutt urged\nQuezon to recommend the repeal of\nthe law, the enactment of which the\njPilipino President himself had rec\nommended.\nOyster Eating Is Urged\nTo Obtain World Peace\nCOLCHESTER, England OP).\u2014A\nsuggestion that world peace might be\nattained by eating oysters was made\nby Sir Holman .Gregory, former re\ncorder of London, at the local feast\ncelebrating opening of the oyster\nseason.\n\u201cNowadays,\u201d he declared, \"th\u00ab\nworld is bubbling, and there seems no\nchance of settling down. What a pity\nit is that we cannot cultivate enough\noysters to give to our politicians\nthroughout the world and get them\ninto the state of mind that we are Id\nat this moment.\u201d\nSpiritual Misuied.\nNo word in our vocabulary has\nprobably suffered so much from mis\nuse as the word \u201cspiritual.\u201d Carica\ntures so grotesque and ao repellent\nhave been exhibited of the spiritual\nin character as at times to disgust\nthe world with the whole Idea, and to\nbring about appalling moral reactions\nk\nEurope\u2019s Crisis Retarded\nBritain's \u201cWatchful Waiting\u201d Is Delaying a War-or-Peace Crisis in Europe,- Says French Observer.\nHitler and Mussolini, He Says, Are Tightening Their Grip on the Vital Mediterranean.\n\nA Spanish oil tanker torpedoed off Africa.\n\nBy PERTINAX.\nAVE we seen the last of the\nshilly-shallying of Great\nBritain and France in their\ndealings with the totalitarian\nstates\u2014and particularly with Italy,\nwhich is leading the attack against\n\u201cBolshevism\u201d in the Spanish penin\nsula? There have been a number of\nrecent indications that the attitude\nof the French and British was hard\nening. But we must always remem\nber that Premier Neville Chamber\nlain and his cabinet colleagues have\nalways in mind the idea of postpon\ning to next year, if they can, the set\ntlement of the Mediterranean issue.\n\"Next year,\u201d the British say, \u201cwe\nshall be stronger both in a military\nand a political sense. Our naval and\nair armaments, although not yet com\nplete. nevertheless will have been\nbrought to a high degree of efficiency.\nYou French criticize our delaying\nmethods, our policy of \u2018non-inter\nvention,\u2019 as highly dangerous. As\nyou explain, they give both dictators\nample time to strengthen and extend\ntheir positions in the Mediterranean,\nmenacing lines of communication\nwhich are truly essential to the Brit\nish and French oversea empires.\n\u201cBut our procrastination will, at\nany rate, have had a favorable result\n\u2014it will have proved to the mass of\nour population that there is no choice\nleft for us but to resort to the most\ndrastic mode of action. Therefore it\nwill be possible, when we can no\nlonger delay, for the British govern\nment to secure that national unanim\nity which we always consider an es\nsential requirement of our defense\nwhenever we are forced to resort to\narms.\n\u201cMeanwhile, the economic structure\nof both totalitarian states will be\nsteadily disintegrating. Then, per\nhaps, they will be brought to book\nwithout our being compelled to use\nforcible means\u2014that is, will be led\nto strike some compromise whereby\nour essential interests will be safe\nguarded.\u201d\nPostpone Day of Reckoning.\nSuch is the line of reasoning that\ncrops up whenever a French states\nman talks to one of the ministers of\nDowning Street. The Frenchman may\nhave inferred from some British min\nisterial pronouncement or from some\npractical stroke of British diplomacy,\nthat the hour has struck for definite\naction, that all temporizing has final\nly been given up by the foreign of\nfice: but then is forced to realize\nanew that British policy does not\nproceed along a straight line\u2014that it\nremains fundamentally empirical and\nthat, on the whole, it strives to post\npone the day of reckoning,\nj Nevertheless, since last August, a\ngreat change has come to pass. \"Vhat\nhas been called Mediterranean \u201cpi\nracy\" accounts for it. Mediterranean\npiracy: this was the term applied to\nthe indiscriminate sinking of cargo\nboats of various nationalties by sub\nmarines and airplanes. At once the\nBritsh government\u2014which for nearly\na century and a half has wielded un\nbroken power on the seven seas\u2014had\nto consider what it would mean for the\nempire to have its trade routes ex\nposed to the attacks of ruthless rivals.\nBut whence came the torpedoes that\nsent so many ships to the bottom in\nthe Mediterranean? Officially, no\ncharge whatever was laid at the door\nof any government. No government\nwas named and held responsible ex\ncept by Soviet Russia, which ordered\nher Ambassador in Rome to deliver a\nnote of protest.\nHowever, no doubt was entertained,\nin either London or Paris, about the\nidentity of the attackers. The French\ngovernment had in its possession defi\nnite Information that of the four sub\nmarines which played such havoc at\nleast two had been constructed in\nItalian naval yards not long before, to\nthe order of a foreign government, and\nthat on completion had been sud\ndenly transferred to the navy of Gen.\nFranco, most probably with Italian\ncrews on board. The figures and let\nters painted on their hulls are known.\nSimilar details have reached the ad\nmiralty in Whitehall.\nThus the British and French have\nbeen treated to a most impressive dem\nonstration of what control of the Med\niterranean by an enemy nation would\nmean in war time. And our British\nfriends sadly needed some such stimu\nlation of their imaginative powers.\nHaving learfied their lesson, they have\nbegun to ponder the various steps\ntaken by the Italian and German gov\nernments since last June, when both\nstruck a fatal blow at the system of\ninternational control that at the time\nwas being enforced off the Spanish\nshores.\nAfter all, was it excessive to assume\nthat the rulers in Rome and Berlin\nhad followed a definite purpose\u2014at\nfirst, to get rid of the watch kept by\nBritish and French in co-operation\nwith German and Italian units on the\nmaritime avenues of Spain, and then\nto substitute for it a blockade of their\nI\nuniii ou w cut uii me v aiciitia gw\nemment from all outside supplies?\nAt last the British government was\nmoved out of its passivity and. not\nwithstanding the German and Italian\nrefusal to attend, the Conference of\nNyon was summoned. Here nine Med\niterranean powers gave British and\nFrench squadrons the mandate to de\nstroy summarily every attacking ship\nor airplane. Mussolini gave way, with\na deep sense of humiliation. And he\nwas forced to attend, 10 days later, a\nconvention clearly intended to keep\nhim within bounds.\nHad he surrendered? Was he about\nto revise his wild schemes of terri\ntorial and political upheaval? Was\nhe about to perceive that such an\nupheaval could not fail to prove more\nadvantageous to the pan-Germanist\npolicy than to his own? Would he\nrealize that his Roman Empire, in\nsuch a case, would be overshadowed\nby Germanic domination and that he\nhad better seek some kind of com\npromise with the Western powers?\nWith such thoughts as these, the\ndeep-rooted optimism of the British\nministers was revived and once more\nblossomed. On September 20 Mr.\nEden, in a talk with Mr. Delbos, the\nFrench foreign minister, harped on\nthe old theme that for the present\nthere was no necessity of urging Italy\nto withdraw from Spain the 80.000\nor 90,000 men who fight under Gen.\nFranco, or to evacuate the Island of\nMajorca and other points of vantage.\n\u201cLet Us Wait,\u201d Says Eden.\n\u201cLet us wait,\u201d said Mr. Eden, \u201cuntil\nthe Spanish Nationalists have won\ntheir victory. Then we shall know\nfor certain whether the Italian troops,\nbeing deprived of all plausible mo\ntives for- remaining where they are,\nwill at last re-embark or, alternatively,\nmore deeply intrench themselves.\u201d\n\"But,\u201d retorted Mr. Delbos, \"mean\nwhile they will have been given a\nlong respite and it will be all the\nmore difficult to compel them to clear\nout. And the same remark applies\nto the Germans in Spanish Morocco,\nin the Canary Islands, at Ifni and in\nthe Rio de Oro.\u201d\nMr. Eden was shaken in his im\nperturbability by the French foreign\nminister's exhortations. He hastened\nback to London (\"I shall be more use\nful there than in Geneva!\u201d). Four\ndays later the French Charge d'Af\nfaires, with the full support of his\nBritish colleague, proposed to Italy\nthat the problem of the volunteers\nshould be singled out for direct treat\nment in an Anglo-French-Italian ne\ngotiation.\nA week afterward a joint note of\nthe British and French governments\nofficially formulated that offer. The\nrefusal of Italy was wrapped up in\nuie Boitemng iormmas oi aipiomacy,\nbut it was a refusal Just the same.\nThen, on October 20, Italy slightly\nchanged its attitude and, in deference\nto French and British wishes, it agreed\nthat the recall of volunteers ought\nto take precedence over the granting\nof belligerent rights to Salamanca and\nValencia, but without indicating how\nmany men would be involved in such\na move. The meeting of the Non-In\ntervention Committee in London fol\nlowed, and Italy felt that once again\nthe way was open to play for time\nby raising all kinds of secondary\nissues and thus, behind the screen\nof diplomatic controversy, to prepare\nsafely for a final victory in the Span\nish peninsula.\nPresses Military Preparations.\nAll sort of huge military prepara\ntions on Italian territory pointed to\nthe Duce\u2019s resolution to do his utmost\nto achieve the rout of the Valencia\ngovernment before the end of the\nyear\u2014a resolution that, at this writ\ning, the discussions of the Non-Inter\nvention Committee do not appear\nlikely to counteract seriously.\nA few weeks ago the French consul\nin Malaga was ordered by the nation\nalist authorities to keep to his house.\nApparently, the penalty was inflicted\nupon him because the French govern\nment had ordered the arrest, in French\nterritory, of Comdr. Truncoso, military\ngovernor of Irun, who had organized\na raid on a government submarine in\nthe harbor of Brest. Later on. Gen.\nFranco had to recognize that Comdr.\nTruncoso\u2019s action could not be de\nfended\u2014yet the French consul was\nnot released. The only possible ex\nplanation is that he was put under\nlock and key because, had he been\nleft at large, he would have observed\nthe arrival of Italian troops and war\nmaterial in the neighborhood of Mal\naga, a great port.\nIn addition, deeds of piracy are still\nbeing recorded. On October 4, the\nBritish cruiser Basilisk was attacked\nbetween Malaga and Valencia, and\u2014\nnotwithstanding the denial that Lon\ndon issued for the sake of Anglo\nGerman relations\u2014it can be added\nthat the cruiser\u2019s assailant, the Ger\nman submarine U-24 of Wilhelms\nhaven, was sent to the bottom.\nOn October 24, a French submarine\nchaser had the worst of an encounter\nwith an unidentified airplane off\nMinorca, and the French admiralty\nhad to admit that in this juncture its\npatrol had proved inadequate.\nDid Mussolini, during his stay in\nBerlin, succeed in obtaining from\nAdolf Hitler and Herman Goering that\npromise of unlimited military assist\nance which, hitherto, he had vainly\nendeavored to get from them? Or are\nboth dictators convinced that their\nintervention into Spanish affairs can\nbe continued indefinitely with im\npunity? Do they feel that the French\nand British cabinets will never make\nup their minds to say: \"So far and\nno farther!\u2019\u2019? Do they think that\nthey will have to face only a trial of\nwill, and never a trial of strength?\nWe may ignore the question of whether\nformal pledges have or have not been\nexchanged between Hitler, Mussolini\nand Goering\u2014but it is only safe to\nsuppose that both dictatorial regimes\nare now united by a military bond.\nWe must always be prepared for the\nworst.\nTo Continue War Exploitation.\nIt is plain that Italy and Germany\nare determined to continue to exploit\nthe Spanish civil war. By this means\nthey can menace the mobilization of\nthe French Army across the Mediter\nranean. They can interfere with the\nvital communications of France with\nNorthern Africa and of Great Britain\nwith the Levant, with Egypt and with\nher Asiatic possessions. They can\nplace the two great Western powers\non the defensive and compel them to\nabandon their policy of collective se\ncurity policy, which, so far, has\nchecked the expansion of pan-Ger\nmanism in Central and Eastern Eu\nrope.\nParis and London are now faced\nby this prospect. They have lived\nhitherto in the belief that they could\ndodge the issue and take shelter In the\nopportunism of the policy of so-called\nnon-intervention. Now they cannot\nany longer shut their eyes to the harsh\nreality: Italy and presumably Ger-\nmany seemingly would risk war rather\nthan retrace their steps.\nThe steady massing of Italian troops\nin Libya tells the whole tale. Mus\nsolini has never forgotten that in the\nautumn of 1935 he was at the mercy\nof France and England, that enforce\nment of the oil sanction would have\nbeen enough to break him, his regime\nand his country. He believes that in\nthe present circumstances he could,\nto say the least, inflict enormous dam\nage upon his enemies.\nWhat, ran trn Hrv nro PrannVi\nBritish? We must put ourselves in a\nposition to make the Duce and Der\nFuehrer take a more accurate view of\nwhat a European conflict would mean\nto them. If possible, we must put into\naction those rational forces which, in\nBerlin especially, have sometimes suc\nceeded in making themselves heard.\nThe French government cannot do\notherwise in the long run than unlock\nthe Fyrenean frontier and allow volun\nteers and war material to rush to the\nrescue of the Valencia government.\nHowever, it is likely that they will not\nrush in such masses or quantities as to\ncounterbalance the new, freer influx\nof Italian military assistance to Gen.\nFranco.\nOf the truly drastic countermeas\nures that F'rance and England could\nwell carry out, the most important is\nthe occupation of Minorca, in the\nBalearic Islands, and of Spanish Mo\nrocco. At once Italy and Germany\nwould understand that the two mari\ntime nations have been roused from\ntheir lethargy and that serious busi\nness is meant. Through these two\noperations a good deal might be done\nto re-establish \u201cstrategic equilibrium\u201d\nin the Mediterranean. All the subma\nrine bases, aerodromes, electric plants,\noil depots and radio stations erected\nby the intruders would be swept off\nat one single stroke.\nCould Afford to Temporize.\nThen we could afford to temporize\nuntil next year\u2014until British rearm\nament has made headway\u2014and quiet\nly watch developments, especially If\nco-operation with Soviet Russia and\nthe Danubian states became something\nmore than a pious aspiration. Instead\nof working against us, time would help\nus, because, while our material\nstrength would be on the increase,\nanother winter would further exhaust,\nin the economic sense, the German\nReich and the F\u2019ascist regime.\nBut to wait indefinitely on the leaky\ndam of nonintervention (to use Mr.\nEden's words in Geneva) would lead\nus straight to disaster, since Italy\ncould be trusted to make use of the\ndelay in order to strengthen her posi\ntion in the Western Mediterranean,\nreshape Spain under dictatorial insti\ntutions and bring a Spanish army\ninto alignment flong the Pyrenees.\nSuch moves would go far toward\noffsetting any additional military\npower that, meanwhile, the British\nand the French might have brought\ninto being.\nWill not Minorca fall. into Italian\nhands before France has taken the\ninitiative? Such a stroke by II Duce\nwould have a telling effect on events\nin Europe. It would be a hard lesson\u2014\nbut it might also be the final alarm\nthat would bring John Bull out of his\nlethargy. At any rate, the days of\nshort-sighted British empiricism are\nnumbered.\n(OeevrisM. utw\ni\nAirplane Opens Up New Frontier\nOf Mining in Canada\u2019s Northwest\nOTTAWA, Canada.\u2014Just as the cov\nered wagon and pack train of pioneer\ndays carried the tide of civilization\nwestward on the North American con\ntinent, so the airplane of today is\nopening up a new mining frontier in\nthe Canadian Northwest Territories.\nLong regarded only as a region of ice\nand snow, this vast expanse, which\nembraces more than one-third of all\nCanada, is now destined to play an\nimportant role in the economic life of\nthe Dominion due to the introduction\nof aerial transportation. Many area)\nonce almost inaccessible are now\nwithin a few hours\u2019 flying time from\nlarge centers of population, and regions\nrich in minerals of economic im\nportance\u2014radium, copper, nickel, gold,\nlead, zinc and silver\u2014await the pros\npector.\nThe year 1929 was the turning point\nin the affairs of the Northwest Terri\ntories, when mineral exploration com\npanies demonstrated that the airplane\ncould be used to advantage in these\nnorthern latitudes. The range of the\nprospector's activities had previously\nbeen restricted mainly to lands in close\nproximity to rivers and lakes, and little\nwas known of the country back from\nnavigable waters. With the advent of\naerial transportation the movement of\nthe prospector became more wide\nspread and the necessity arose for\nmaps far more detailed than those\nthen available. By resorting to the\nairplane and the modem science of\nmap-making, Including aerial photog\nrahpy, topographical and geological\nmapping were speeded up. In 1930\nand 1931 an area of 11,000 square miles\nto the east of Great Bear Lake was\nphotographed, and, last year, to give\nthe most reoeat example, an area of\n4\n17,500 square miles to the east of\nYellowknife River.\nPrevious to 1929 the principle min\neral developments in the Northwest\nTerritories were the location and par\ntial development of lead-zinc deposits\nnear Pine Point, Great Slave Lake, and\nthe discovery of oil at a point about\n50 miles below Norman on the\nMackenzie River, where there are now\ntwo producing wells. As a result of\naerial explorations carried out in 1929,\ncopper-sulphide deposits were discov\nered in the area between Great Bear\nLake and the Coppermine River, and\nthis was followed by a notable discov\nery of pitchblende-silver deposits, from\nwhich radium is obtained, at La Bine\nPoint, on the eastern side of Great\nBear Lake, in May, 1930. In 1935 gold\nwas discovered near the mouth of Yel\nlowknife River and on Outpost Island,\nand also in the vicinity of Taltson\nRiver on the south shore of Great\nSlave Lake. In the Fall of 1936 a gold\nstrike was reported at Gordon Lake, 50\nmiles northeast of Yellowknife Bay,\nwhich seems likely to rank as one of\nthe most important finds in recent\nyears. A nickel and cobalt-bearing\nmineral deposit has been located a few\nmiles east of the point where the\nFrancois River enters the eastern arm\nof Great Slave Lake.\nAccording to recent reports, Can\nada\u2019s northern mineral front continues\nto be the scene of great activity, and\naerial transportation companies are\nbusily engaged In carrying freight,\nsupplies and men to remote areas. In\nmost of the mining country of the\nNorth there are numerous lakes which\nprovide suitable landing for aircraft\nwith floats in Summer and with skis\nIn Winter..\n1\nROOSEVELT CAN REVEAL\nPATH TO SOUND POLICYj\nClouds of Inflation, Though Banked\nAbout Nation, May Be Lifted in\nMessage to Congress.\nBy MARK SULLIVAN.\nCONGRESS assembles tomorrow.\nWithin a day or two after\nward, presumably, President\nRoosevelt will address it. Soon\nthereafter will emerge the controlling\nfactor of the session\u2014the degree to\nwhich Congress is willing to accept\nthe President\u2019s ideas.\nA majority of Congress, and even\na majority of the President\u2019s own party\nin Congress, do not think habitually\nas he does. But for upward of three\nyears Congress was willing to accept\nmeasures as written by the President\u2019s\nadvisers. That condition came to an\nend on a date that can be identified\nexactly. It was February 5 last, the\nday when Mr. Roosevelt sent to Con\ngress his measure to change the Su\npreme Court. From then on, until the\nregular session ended in August, Con\ngress was increasingly an Independent\nbody.\nSince August, has anything hap\npened that would increase the Presi\ndent\u2019s authority over Congress?\nHardly. The one conspicuous event\nin this field since August was the tur\nmoil over the appointment of Mr.\nBlack to the Supreme Court. That\nwas hardly likely to increase the Pres\nident\u2019s prestige.\nWhat President Roosevelt says to\nCongress in his address during the\ncoming week, and what Congress does\nduring the session, will inevitably be\ninfluenced largely by one condition,\nthe business recession.\nCost of Living High Now.\nThe recession in which the country\nis now involved is not comparable to\nthe depression in which Mr. Roosevelt\ntook office on March 4, 1933. The\npresent recession ought not to become\nanything near so serious as that. The\ndifference between the two economic\nphenomena is measured by the dis\ntance between the two words, \u201creces\nsion\u201d and \"depression.\u201d Nevertheless,\nthe recession is a serious matter for\nthe country and for Mr. Roosevelt.\nThis recession comes at a time when\ncost of living is high, while in 1933 the\ncost of living was low. This recession\ncomes at a time when the national\ndebt is about 36 billions, while the debt\nin 1932 was only 22 billions.\nWhat will Mr. Roosevelt propose to\ndo? Before this recession came, or at\nleast before Mr. Roosevelt and and\nthe country were aware of it, Mr.\nRoosevelt seemed determined to bal\nance the budget. He did not say so\ndirectly himself, but some of his\nclosest and most highly placed ad\nvisers said it, presumably with Mr.\nRoosevelt\u2019s approval. Balancing the\nbudget had been half predicted, al\nmost half promised, each year since\nMr. Roosevelt became President. In\ndeed, the semi-predicting and semi\npromising began before: it began dur\ning 1932 when Mr. Roosevelt was a\ncandidate.\nBalancing the budget, as everybody\nknows, means simply spending no\nmore money than the Government\nreceives in taxes. Let us see how\nthis possibly is affected by business re\ncession.\nWhat to Do With Jobless?\nBusiness recession means more per\nsons out of work. If Mr. Roosevelt\nsticks to his frequently announced\npolicy that the Federal Government\nshould see to it that all unemployed\nare cared for\u2014if Mr. Roosevelt sticks\nto that policy, more unemployment\nmeans more money paid out of the\nFederal Treasury.\nAt the same time business recession\nmeans a smaller amount of money\nreceived by the Federal Government in\ntaxes. For diminished activity of gen\neral business means less profits, and\nit is out of profits very largely that\ntaxes come.\nObviously, most obviously, dimin\nished receipts by the Federal Treas\nury, accompanied by increased de\nmand upon the Federal Treasury,\ndoes not mean a balanced budget. It\nmeans the opposite. If the admin\nistration is to stick to its policy of\nhaving the Federal Government re\nsponsible for taking care of unem\nployment, and if the money for that\npurpose does not come in other taxa\ntion. then the only answer is more\nborrowing.\n\u201cBorrowing,\u201d incidentally, is hardly\nthe correct word for the way by\nwhich the Federal Government gets\nmoney. It does borrow some, but\nthe more exact word for the source\nof much of the Federal Government's\nmoney would be \u201cmanufacturing.\u201d\nThe Federal Government, in effect,\ncreates new money by printing Gov\nernment bonds. Whatever the word,\nthe borrowing of money or the creat\ning of new money, or both, comes\nto the same end. It means larger\nGovernment debt. It means still larger\nGovernment debt at a time when\nthat debt is already larger than ever\nin the country\u2019s history.\nInflation Can Be Avoided.\nMore Government debt, every econ\nomist tells us, is the path toward\none form of inflation, toward higher\nprices for practically everything. Now\nana recently, when prices have been\ngoing down rapidly, one frequently\nhears that the prophets w\u2019ho have been\npredicting inflation are being proved\nwrong. The present and recent course\nof prices has been in directly the oppo\nsite direction from inflation. Never\ntheless, I imagine that most of the\neconomists who have been predicting\ninflation would say we are a little\nnearer to the condition now than ever\nbefore. Yet let no one conclude posi\ntively that Inflation and high prices\nare certain. It is always possible\nthat the world, including America,\nmight take the path back to economic\nand fiscal sanity. If America is to\ntake that path, we should find it\npointed out in the address Mr. Roose\nvelt makes to Confess in a few days.\nPresident Roosevelt, in calling the\ncoming extra session of Congress,\nmentioned measures which he espe\ncially desired Congress to pass. Let\nus see how these proposals, and the\nprospect of Congress enacting them,\nare affected by the business recession\nwhich descended upon the country\nbetween the time when Mr. Roosevelt\ncalled the extra session, October 12,\nand the time the session comes into\nbeing, next Monday.\nOne of Mr. Roosevelt's proposals\nis crop control. \u2018\u2018Crop control\u201d means\ncrop limitation. It means smaller\ncrops\u2014each farmer to raise only so\nmuch of certain crops as the Federal\nGovernment tells him to raise. For\ngetting the farmers to practice this\nlimitation there are two methods about\nthe choice of which argument is high\nand will continue to be high. One\nmethod is voluntary\u2014the Government\nwin pay farmen certain specified\namount* in cash in return for their\npromises to reduce their acreage. The\nother method Is compulsory\u2014farmers\nto plant only so much as the quota\nImposed by the Government, under\npenalty of punitive taxes or other\nmethods of compulsion.\nCompulsion Hard to Impose.\nThe argument, it is probable, will\nend, as respects most of the crops\naffected, in favor of the voluntary\nform of limitation. Compulsion 1a\nnot as easy to impose as it was when\nMr. Roosevelt took office, when the\ncountry was in despair and ready to\naccept any requirement of Govern\nment.\nBut even if the farmers are willing\nto accept any method of crop limita\ntion, whether voluntary or compulsory,\nwill the country as a whole be willing\nto accept it? Crop control means a\nhigher level of prices for crops, for\nfood\u2014that is the purpose of it. And\nwill the country be willing to accept\nthis policy at a time when the cost\nof living is high? Most of the country\nwas willing, or at least did not make\nserious outcry, when crop control was\nfirst introduced, in 1933; but at that\ntime cost of living was low.\nOne of the major measures for\nwhich President Roosevelt has called\nCongress into special session is the\nenactment of a \u201cwage and hour\u201d bill.\nThat is, a measure which shall say\nthat workers must not work more\nthan a certain number of hours per\nweek the number commonly dis\nls 40\u2014and that no worker\nshall be paid a wage lower than a\ncertain minimum.\nFor the minimum wage part of the\nmeasure there is much support.\nWorkers generally like it. Most em\nployers like it\u2014it would enable them\nto pay a decent wage without suffer\nmg from the unfair competition of\nchiselers\u201d whose onlv art. nf rnmnoti\ntion consists of underpaying their\nlabor. Public opinion generally favors\nthe minimum wage\u2014though it is con\nceded there are serious difficulties in\nfixing one minimum wage appropriate\nfor one industry and another appro\npriate for another industry, one mini\nmum wage for one section of the coun\ntry, another minimum for another\nsection. A minimum wage law suffi\nciently simple; or better, a system by\nwhich each State can fix its own mini\nmum and have the Federal Govern\nment protect each State\u2019s standard\u2014\nwould be favorably received and would\nbe practicable.\nMaximum Hours Difficult.\nAs to the maximum hours part of\nthe proposed measure, there is gen\neral assent to that too, in principle.\nVet some of the maximums proposed\nrun contrary to the common man\u2019s\nideas. One proposal is that no worker\nshall be permitted to work more than\n30 hours a week.\nThe wage and hour bill as originally\nintroduced went much farther than\nmerely fixing a minimum wage and a\nmaximum of hours. The measure as\noriginally introduced would have given\nto a board of five men in Washington\npractically autocratic power over all\nIndustry and all the details of all in\n.dustry. The measure as originally in\ntroduced went in some respects as\nfar in the control of industry as N.\nR. A. During the period since the\nSenate passed the measure. July 31,\nand the sitting of the special session\nof Congress to enable the House to\npass it, support for the measure has\ndiminished. Many labor unions and\nlabor leaders have come to disapprove\nit; the recent national conventiol of\nthe American Federation of Labor\nformerly disapproved it. The reason\nfor opposition by labor leaders may be\nself-interest; they foresee that if the\nGovernment is to have as much con\ntrol over wages as the original wage\nand hour measure would have given\nthe Government, there would be little\nreason left for the existence of labor\nleaders or for collective bargaining.\nWithout doubt the discussion of the\nwage and hour measure in the com\ning Congress will be in the direction\nof limiting its scope. The measure\nthat the House will pass, and the final\nmeasure that becomes law, will be\nmuch simpler than the original pro\nposal.\n(Copyright, 1937.)\nlriple Alliance\n(Continued From First Page.)\nlosophy in the methods adopted by\nItaly, Ethiopia, Japan and China\nmight appeal to nations which have old\nscores to settle with their neighbors.\nIt is for all these reasons that Wash\nington is not inclined to treat lightly\nthe Rome-Berlin-Tokio axis. The ad\nministration recognizes the dangerous\nimplications, and is aware what a\ncomplete confusion might be created\nin the world if this new alliance is\nsuccessful in obtaining all the dicta\ntors vant.\nThere is no unity of policies and of\nviews between Great Britain and\nFrance, which are the pivots of Euro\npean democracy. In the light of what\nis going on in Europe, the State De\npartment feels that the Western pow\ners will be forced to yield every time\nHitler and Mussolini hold out their\nmailed fists.\nWashington is not concerned over\nthe fact that France and Great Brit\nain might have to yield a few thousand\nsquare miles of their African posses\nsions. It is concerned over the fact\nthat the example set by a successful\nGerman-Italian-Japanese policy might\nbecome a standard to be followed by\nother nations.\n(Copyright. 1937.)\nFascism\n(Continued From First Page.)\n\"Supreme Dictator\u201d of an avowed to\ntalitarian state in America, and if his\nexample is followed, as it surely will be,\nby other Latin American dictators,\nconsequences of the most serious sort\nwill follow for the United States. Such\na development would mean the death\nof Pan Americanism. It would also\nmean the death of the century-old pol\nicy of the United States of compelling\nEurope to keep \"hands off\u201d the states\nof Latin America. Except for Cuba and\none or two other countries, the ties\nbinding the United States to the re\npublics of the South are not very\nstrong. It is doubtful if they could\nkeep the continent bound to democ\nracy against the puQ of the community\nof Interest and the common purpose\nthat would come into .being between\nthe newly organized Fascist states of\nAmerica and their longer-established\nprototypes in Europe.","height":"31236","width":"22344"}}
